		<section>
			<section.front>
				<doc.title toc-guid="Id71f7aec682311ea83aee46e6decbb85">
					<head parent="doc.title">
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<label.name>§ </label.name>
						<label.designator>6:2.</label.designator>
						<headtext>Matters of common knowledge</headtext>
						<eos/>
						<eop/>
					</head>
				</doc.title>
			</section.front>
			<section.body>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>The court may judicially notice facts of common knowledge that are known to be certain and indisputable or that are subject to verification.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7833e5d074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>A judge is “refreshing the judicial memory” when he consults a source regarding a fact. <eos/>
						<bos/>This is entirely a fiction since the judge may take judicial notice of a fact which he never knew before. <eos/>
						<bos/>The judge has broad discretion in taking judicial notice, especially in areas where he will refer to a source to refresh his judicial recollection. <eos/>
						<bos/>A judge should never take judicial notice of any fact that may be disproved.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I78340ce074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] Once a court takes judicial notice, a party may not introduce contrary evidence.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I78340ce174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>] The court may take judicial notice in situations like ruling on motions where evidence could not be used. <eos/>
						<bos/>The court will disregard any allegation that contradicts anything of which the court took judicial notice. <eos/>
						<bos/>This may result in dismissal of the petition.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I78340ce274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<?page no="158"?>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>The judge should not take judicial notice of a disputed fact, but jurisdictions vary on when there is a dispute. <eos/>
						<bos/>For example, the Georgia Court of Appeals dismissed a petition on demurrer because a trial court took judicial notice of the fact that a train headlight and automobile headlights would cross each other without effect.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I78340ce374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>] A federal court refused to take judicial notice of the same fact.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I78340ce474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">6</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>The cases in this area cover many areas of human experience. <eos/>
						<bos/>For example, it is common knowledge that: kerosene is used for cooking, heating, and lighting purposes;[<footnote.reference refid="I783433f074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">7</footnote.reference>] scatter rugs have a tendency to slide on a smooth surface;[<footnote.reference refid="I783433f174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">8</footnote.reference>] excessive use of intoxicants impairs the operator of a motor vehicle,[<footnote.reference refid="I783433f274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">9</footnote.reference>] <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“an automobile is a heavy metal vehicle, and for it to be overturned upon the person of a female would likely crush and inflict serious or mortal wounds upon her”<end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>;[<footnote.reference refid="I783433f374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">10</footnote.reference>] and “termination of pregnancy” means the pregnancy ended by abortion or miscarriage.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I783433f474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">11</footnote.reference>] Our common knowledge includes laws of nature and the effect of natural forces,[<footnote.reference refid="I783433f574d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">12</footnote.reference>] geographical facts,[<footnote.reference refid="I78345b0074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">13</footnote.reference>] historical facts,[<footnote.reference refid="I78345b0174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">14</footnote.reference>] statistical facts,[<footnote.reference refid="I7834821074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">15</footnote.reference>
						<?page no="159"?>] abbreviations,[<footnote.reference refid="I7834821174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">16</footnote.reference>] calendar,[<footnote.reference refid="I7834821274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">17</footnote.reference>] certain customs and usages,[<footnote.reference refid="I7834821374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">18</footnote.reference>] and the intoxicating character of certain alcoholic beverages.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7834821474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">19</footnote.reference>] The Georgia Court of Appeals authorized a trial court to take judicial notice of the recent deaths of the trial judge and his court reporter because it was a matter of public knowledge and it satisfied the requirements of <cite.query w-src-number="0287017098" w-seq-number="00053" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST50-2-21" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Icdecbde074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 50-2-21(b)(5)</cite.query>.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7834a92074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">20</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>In a prosecution for driving under the influence of alcohol, a trial court may judicially notice that the standardized horizontal gaze nystagmus test has been verified.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7834a92174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">21</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Sometimes, the court may need to consult reference sources to ascertain a fact, especially for scientific facts or principles[<footnote.reference refid="I7834a92274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">22</footnote.reference>] and medical facts.[<eos/>
						<?page no="160"?>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7834a92374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">23</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<feature.para.block>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<head parent="para">
							<headtext>
								<bold>Practice Tip:</bold>
							</headtext>
						</head>
						<paratext>Especially for scientific facts, counsel should have a source of information available for the judge before making a request for judicial notice.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</feature.para.block>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>In ascertaining a fact, the judge may resort to any helpful source of knowledge, but should not introduce the source into evidence. <eos/>
						<bos/>Two Georgia cases might cause some confusion here. <eos/>
						<bos/>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017098" w-serial-number="1960123796" w-seq-number="00063" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Icdefa41274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Fields v. Jackson</ital>
						</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I7834d03074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">24</footnote.reference>] the trial court admitted a letter from the Director of the U. S. Naval Observatory stating the time of sunrise on a particular day. <eos/>
						<bos/>The Georgia Court of Appeals held that admitting the letter was harmless error since the court could consult an almanac or other source and could take judicial notice of the time of sunrise on a given day. <eos/>
						<bos/>Oddly, <ital>Pentry v. Addison</ital>[<footnote.reference refid="I7834d03174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">25</footnote.reference>] cited the <cite.query w-src-number="0287017098" w-serial-number="1960123796" w-seq-number="00067" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Icdf23c2274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Fields</ital>
						</cite.query> case as holding that the court could introduce the almanac or other source into evidence after it took judicial of the time of sunrise.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Some areas that are not candidates for judicial notice are the prime rate of interest since the prime rate fluctuates and the particular prime rate at any given moment is not the type of fact normally found within a person&apos;s <begin.quote ID="QT_0004"/>“general knowledge and experience”<end.quote refid="QT_0004"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I7834d03274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">26</footnote.reference>] and the operation of the locking device on a cement truck chutes.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7834f74074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">27</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
			</section.body>
		</section>
