					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017098" w-serial-number="1979106130" w-seq-number="00065" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Icdf0dc9274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">State v. Dancy, 297 N.C. 40, 252 S.E.2d 514 (1979)</cite.query>, the trial judge refused to take judicial notice of the moon condition based on the “Ladies Birthday Almanac.” <eos/>
							<bos/>The Supreme Court did take judicial notice, based on records of the U.S. Naval Observatory. <eos/>
							<bos/>This was a “Lincolnesque” case, since a witness had identified the defendant because the moon was shining bright at 9:45 P.M. on January 30, 1978. <eos/>
							<bos/>The Supreme Court reversed, based on their judicial notice that on that night the moon was in the last quarter and did not rise until midnight.<eos/>
